https://w3id.org/okn/o/sd#description: A configuration of the TopoFlow model calibrated for the Baro region in Ethiopia with pre-set precipitation rates (compressed file) from GLDAS and parameters for start/end of the simulation.
https://w3id.org/okn/o/sd#hasUsageNotes: This Topoflow configuration has ISRIC with data for 7 soil layers, and using data from the top 3. The start and end dates must be compatible with the data selected. For example, if the data is from 2017 the start date cannot be 2018" There is a 'CHECK_STABILITY' flag that you can set in some of the input configuration files (channels_kin_wave and infil_richards_1d). Since there is no way to predict stable time step size in advance, we have calculated it by trial and error to find the largest value that makes the model work. Once this value is set up, the CHECK_STABILITY flag may be switched to 'No' to speed up the execution of the model. The vertical spacing in the infiltration component (set via dz and nz) layers needs to be small to handle a wide range of rainfall values, but this means the timestep (dt) also needs to be smaller to keep the model stable

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab: Configuration setup for calculating the Standardized Precipitation Evapotranspiration Index from GLDAS data
https://w3id.org/okn/o/sd#description:
This simple configuration uses GLDAS data to calculate the standardized precipitation evapotranspiration index over South Sudan and Ethiopia. 

The SPEI considers not only precipitation but also evapotranspiration (PET) data on its calculation, allowing for a more complete approach to explore the effects of climate change on drought conditions. The SPEI can be calculated at several time scales to adapt to the characteristic times of response to drought of target natural and economic systems, allowing determining their resistance to drought. A major advantage of the SPEI over other multiscalar drought indices such as the SPI is that it considers the role of temperature through its influence on potential evapotranspiration. Thus, the SPEI is adequate for assessing the impact of global warming on droughts.
https://w3id.org/okn/o/sd#hasUsageNotes: Please note that the GLDAS data is not long enough for a proper calibration of at least 30 years.
https://w3id.org/okn/o/sd#keywords: climate; drought; index

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab: Configuration setup for calculating  the Standardized Precipitation Index from GLDAS data
https://w3id.org/okn/o/sd#description:
Simple configuration for calulcating  Standardized Precipitation Index from GLDAS dataStandardized Precipitation Index (SPI): The Standardized Precipitation Index (SPI) is a widely used index to characterize meteorological drought on a range of timescales. On short timescales, the SPI is closely related to soil moisture, while at longer timescales, the SPI can be related to groundwater and reservoir storage. The SPI can be compared across regions with markedly different climates. It quantifies observed precipitation as a standardized departure from a selected probability distribution function that models the raw precipitation data. The raw precipitation data are typically fitted to a gamma or a Pearson Type III distribution, and then transformed to a normal distribution. The SPI values can be interpreted as the number of standard deviations by which the observed anomaly deviates from the long-term mean. The SPI can be created for differing periods of 1-to-36 months, using monthly input data. For the operational community, the SPI has been recognized as the standard index that should be available worldwide for quantifying and reporting meteorological drought. Concerns have been raised about the utility of the SPI as a measure of changes in drought associated with climate change, as it does not deal with changes in evapotranspiration. Alternative indices that deal with evapotranspiration have been proposed (see SPEI).

Key Strength
Uses precipitation only; can characterize drought or abnormal wetness at different time scales which correspond with the time availability of different water resources (e.g. soil moisture, snowpack, groundwater, river discharge and reservoir storage)
More comparable across regions with different climates than the Palmer Severity Drought Index (PDSI)
Less complex to calculate than the PDSI

Key Limitations
As a measure of water supply only, the SPI does not account for evapotranspiration, and this limits its ability to capture the effect of increased temperatures (associated with climate change) on moisture demand and availability
Sensitive to the quantity and reliability of the data used to fit the distribution; 30-50 years recommended
Does not consider the intensity of precipitation and its potential impacts on runoff, streamflow, and water availability within the system of interest
Since temeprature is not taken into account, interpret carefully over long time scales.

source: https://climatedataguide.ucar.edu/climate-data/standardized-precipitation-index-spi

https://w3id.org/okn/o/sd#keywords: climate; drought; index

Once this value is set up, the CHECK_STABILITY flag may be switched to 'No' to speed up the execution of the model. The vertical spacing in the infiltration component (set via dz and nz) layers needs to be small to handle a wide range of rainfall values, but this means the timestep (dt) also needs to be smaller to keep the model stable
